# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: trino-presto
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:trino-presto/concepts] To understand Trino, you must first understand the terms and concepts used throughout the Trino documentation.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] While it is easy to understand statements and queries, as an end-user you should have familiarity with concepts such as stages and splits to take full advantage of Trino to execute efficient queries.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] As a Trino administrator or a Trino contributor you should understand how Trino’s concepts of stages map to tasks and how tasks contain a set of drivers which process data.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] This section provides a solid definition for the core concepts referenced throughout Trino, and these sections are sorted from most general to most specific.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The book Trino: The Definitive Guide and the research paper Presto: SQL on Everything can provide further information about Trino and the concepts in use.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Trino is a distributed query engine that processes data in parallel across multiple servers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] There are two types of Trino servers, coordinators and workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The following sections describe these servers and other components of Trino’s architecture.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A Trino cluster consists of several Trino nodes - one coordinator and zero or more workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Users connect to the coordinator with their SQL query tool.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The coordinator collaborates with the workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The coordinator and the workers access the connected data sources.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Processing each query is a stateful operation.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The workload is orchestrated by the coordinator and spread parallel across all workers in the cluster.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Each node runs Trino in one JVM instance, and processing is parallelized further using threads.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Any Trino server in a specific Trino cluster is considered a **node** of the cluster.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Technically this refers to the Java process running the Trino program, but node is often used to refer to the computer running the process due to the recommendation to run only one Trino process per computer.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The Trino coordinator is the server that is responsible for parsing statements, planning queries, and managing Trino worker nodes.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] It is the “brain” of a Trino installation and is also the node to which a client connects to submit statements for execution.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Every Trino installation must have a Trino coordinator alongside one or more Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] For development or testing purposes, a single instance of Trino can be configured to perform both roles.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The coordinator keeps track of the activity on each worker and coordinates the execution of a query.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The coordinator creates a logical model of a query involving a series of stages, which is then translated into a series of connected tasks running on a cluster of Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Coordinators communicate with workers and clients using a REST API.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A Trino worker is a server in a Trino installation, which is responsible for executing tasks and processing data.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Worker nodes fetch data from connectors and exchange intermediate data with each other.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The coordinator is responsible for fetching results from the workers and returning the final results to the client.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When a Trino worker process starts up, it advertises itself to the discovery server in the coordinator, which makes it available to the Trino coordinator for task execution.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Workers communicate with other workers and Trino coordinators using a REST API.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Clients allow you to connect to Trino, submit SQL queries, and receive the results.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Clients can access all configured data sources using catalogs.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Clients are full-featured client applications or client drivers and libraries that allow you to connect with any application supporting that driver, or even your own custom application or script.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Client application that support other query languages or user interface components to build a query, must translate each request to SQL as supported by Trino.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] More details are available in the Trino client documentation.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Trino uses a plugin architecture to extend its capabilities and integrate with various data sources and other systems.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Details about different types of plugins, installation, removal, and other aspects are available in the Plugin documentation.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Trino is a query engine that you can use to query many different data sources.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] They include data lakes and lakehouses, numerous relational database management systems, key-value stores, and many other data stores.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A comprehensive list with more details for each data source is available on the Trino website.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Data sources provide the data for Trino to query.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Configure a catalog with the required Trino connector for the specific data source to access the data.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] With Trino you are ready to use any supported client to query the data sources using SQL and the features of your client.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Throughout this documentation, you’ll read terms such as connector, catalog, schema, and table.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] These fundamental concepts cover Trino’s model of a particular data source and are described in the following section.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A connector adapts Trino to a data source such as a data lake using Hadoop/Hive or Apache Iceberg, or a relational database such as PostgreSQL.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] You can think of a connector the same way you think of a driver for a database.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] It is an implementation of Trino’s service provider interface (SPI), which allows Trino to interact with a resource using a standard API.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Every catalog uses a specific connector.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] If you examine a catalog configuration file, you see that each contains a mandatory property `connector.name` with the value identifying the connector.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A Trino catalog is a collection of configuration properties used to access a specific data source, including the required connector and any other details such as credentials and URL.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Catalogs are defined in properties files stored in the Trino configuration directory.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The name of the properties file determines the name of the catalog.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] For example, the properties file `etc/example.properties` results in a catalog name `example`.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] You can configure and use many catalogs, with different or identical connectors, to access different data sources.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] For example, if you have two data lakes, you can configure two catalogs in a single Trino cluster that both use the Hive connector, allowing you to query data from both clusters, even within the same SQL query.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] You can also use a Hive connector for one catalog to access a data lake, and use the Iceberg connector for another catalog to access the data lakehouse.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Or, you can configure different catalogs to access different PostgreSQL database.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The combination of different catalogs is determined by your needs to access different data sources only.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A catalog contains one or more schemas, which in turn contain objects such as tables, views, or materialized views.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When addressing an objects such as tables in Trino, the fully-qualified name is always rooted in a catalog.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] For example, a fully-qualified table name of `example.test_data.test` refers to the `test` table in the `test_data` schema in the `example` catalog.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Together, a catalog and schema define a set of tables and other objects that can be queried.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When accessing Hive or a relational database such as MySQL with Trino, a schema translates to the same concept in the target database.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Other types of connectors may organize tables into schemas in a way that makes sense for the underlying data source.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A table is a set of unordered rows, which are organized into named columns with types.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] This is the same as in any relational database.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Type mapping from source data to Trino is defined by the connector, varies across connectors, and is documented in the specific connector documentation, for example the type mapping in the PostgreSQL connector.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Trino executes SQL statements and turns these statements into queries, that are executed across a distributed cluster of coordinator and workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Trino executes ANSI-compatible SQL statements.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When the Trino documentation refers to a statement, it is referring to statements as defined in the ANSI SQL standard, which consists of clauses, expressions, and predicates.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Some readers might be curious why this section lists separate concepts for statements and queries.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] This is necessary because, in Trino, statements simply refer to the textual representation of a statement written in SQL.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When a statement is executed, Trino creates a query along with a query plan that is then distributed across a series of Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When Trino parses a statement, it converts it into a query and creates a distributed query plan, which is then realized as a series of interconnected stages running on Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When you retrieve information about a query in Trino, you receive a snapshot of every component that is involved in producing a result set in response to a statement.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The difference between a statement and a query is simple.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A statement can be thought of as the SQL text that is passed to Trino, while a query refers to the configuration and components instantiated to execute that statement.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A query encompasses stages, tasks, splits, connectors, and other components and data sources working in concert to produce a result.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When Trino executes a query, it does so by breaking up the execution into a hierarchy of stages.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] For example, if Trino needs to aggregate data from one billion rows stored in Hive, it does so by creating a root stage to aggregate the output of several other stages, all of which are designed to implement different sections of a distributed query plan.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The hierarchy of stages that comprises a query resembles a tree.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Every query has a root stage, which is responsible for aggregating the output from other stages.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Stages are what the coordinator uses to model a distributed query plan, but stages themselves don’t run on Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] As mentioned in the previous section, stages model a particular section of a distributed query plan, but stages themselves don’t execute on Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] To understand how a stage is executed, you need to understand that a stage is implemented as a series of tasks distributed over a network of Trino workers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Tasks are the “work horse” in the Trino architecture as a distributed query plan is deconstructed into a series of stages, which are then translated to tasks, which then act upon or process splits.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A Trino task has inputs and outputs, and just as a stage can be executed in parallel by a series of tasks, a task is executing in parallel with a series of drivers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Tasks operate on splits, which are sections of a larger data set.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Stages at the lowest level of a distributed query plan retrieve data via splits from connectors, and intermediate stages at a higher level of a distributed query plan retrieve data from other stages.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] When Trino is scheduling a query, the coordinator queries a connector for a list of all splits that are available for a table.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] The coordinator keeps track of which machines are running which tasks, and what splits are being processed by which tasks.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Tasks contain one or more parallel drivers.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Drivers act upon data and combine operators to produce output that is then aggregated by a task and then delivered to another task in another stage.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] A driver is a sequence of operator instances, or you can think of a driver as a physical set of operators in memory.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] It is the lowest level of parallelism in the Trino architecture.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] An operator consumes, transforms and produces data.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] For example, a table scan fetches data from a connector and produces data that can be consumed by other operators, and a filter operator consumes data and produces a subset by applying a predicate over the input data.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Exchanges transfer data between Trino nodes for different stages of a query.
[src:trino-presto/concepts] Tasks produce data into an output buffer and consume data from other tasks using an exchange client.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:trino-presto/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto was originally designed and developed at Facebook, Inc.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] (later renamed Meta) for their data analysts to run interactive queries on its large data warehouse in Apache Hadoop.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] The first four developers were Martin Traverso, Dain Sundstrom, David Phillips, and Eric Hwang.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Before Presto, the data analysts at Facebook relied on Apache Hive for running SQL analytics on their multi-petabyte data warehouse.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Hive was deemed too slow for Facebook's scale and Presto was invented to fill the gap to run fast queries.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Original development started in 2012 and deployed at Facebook later that year.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In November 2013, Facebook announced its open source release.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In 2014, Netflix disclosed they used Presto on 10 petabytes of data stored in the Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3).
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In November, 2016, Amazon announced a service called Athena that was based on Presto.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In 2017, Teradata spun out a company called Starburst Data to commercially support Presto, which included staff acquired from Hadapt in 2014.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Teradata's QueryGrid software allowed Presto to access a Teradata relational database.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In January 2019, the Presto Software Foundation was announced.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] The foundation is a not-for-profit organization for the advancement of the Presto open source distributed SQL query engine.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] At the same time, Presto development forked: PrestoDB maintained by Facebook, and PrestoSQL maintained by the Presto Software Foundation, with some cross pollination of code.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In September 2019, Facebook donated PrestoDB to the Linux Foundation, establishing the Presto Foundation.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Neither the creators of Presto, nor the top contributors and committers, were invited to join this foundation.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] By 2020, all four of the original Presto developers had joined Starburst.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] In December 2020, PrestoSQL was rebranded as Trino, since Facebook had obtained a trademark on the name "Presto" (also donated to the Linux Foundation).
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Another company called Ahana was announced in 2020 to commercialize the PrestoDB fork as a cloud service and was acquired by IBM in 2023.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto's architecture is very similar to other database management systems using cluster computing, sometimes called massively parallel processing (MPP).
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] One coordinator works in sync with multiple workers.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Clients submit SQL statements that are parsed and planned, following which parallel tasks are scheduled to workers.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Workers jointly process rows from the data sources and produce results that are returned to the client.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Compared to the original Apache Hive execution model which used the Hadoop MapReduce mechanism on each query, Presto does not write intermediate results to disk, resulting in a significant speed improvement.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] A Presto query can combine data from multiple sources.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto offers connectors to data sources including files in Alluxio, Hadoop Distributed File System (often called a data lake), Amazon S3, MySQL, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Amazon Redshift, Apache Kudu, Apache Phoenix, Apache Kafka, Apache Cassandra, Apache Accumulo, MongoDB and Redis.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Unlike other Hadoop distribution-specific tools, such as Apache Impala, Presto can work with any variant of Hadoop or without it.
[src:trino-presto/presto-sql-query-engine] Presto supports separation of compute and storage and may be deployed on-premises or using cloud computing.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Generally, the query optimizer cannot be accessed directly by users: once queries are submitted to the database server, and parsed by the parser, they are then passed to the query optimizer where optimization occurs.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] However, some database engines allow guiding the query optimizer with hints.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] A query is a request for information from a database.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Since database structures are complex, in most cases, and especially for not-very-simple queries, the needed data for a query can be collected from a database by accessing it in different ways, through different data-structures, and in different orders.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Each different way typically requires different processing time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Processing times of the same query may have large variance, from a fraction of a second to hours, depending on the chosen method.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The purpose of query optimization, which is an automated process, is to find the way to process a given query in minimum time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The large possible variance in time justifies performing query optimization, though finding the exact optimal query plan, among all possibilities, is typically very complex, time-consuming by itself, may be too costly, and often practically impossible.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Thus query optimization typically tries to approximate the optimum by comparing several common-sense alternatives to provide in a reasonable time a "good enough" plan which typically does not deviate much from the best possible result.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] There is a trade-off between the amount of time spent figuring out the best query plan and the quality of the choice; the optimizer may not choose the best answer on its own.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Different qualities of database management systems have different ways of balancing these two.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Cost-based query optimizers evaluate the resource footprint of various query plans and use this as the basis for plan selection.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] These assign an estimated "cost" to each possible query plan, and choose the plan with the smallest cost.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Costs are used to estimate the runtime cost of evaluating the query, in terms of the number of I/O operations required, CPU path length, amount of disk buffer space, disk storage service time, and interconnect usage between units of parallelism, and other factors determined from the data dictionary.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The set of query plans examined is formed by examining the possible access paths (e.g., primary index access, secondary index access, full file scan) and various relational table join techniques (e.g., merge join, hash join, product join).
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The search space can become quite large depending on the complexity of the SQL query.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] These consist of logical optimization—which generates a sequence of relational algebra to solve the query—and physical optimization—which is used to determine the means of carrying out each operation.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Most query optimizers represent query plans as a tree of "plan nodes".
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] A plan node encapsulates a single operation that is required to execute the query.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The nodes are arranged as a tree, in which intermediate results flow from the bottom of the tree to the top.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Each node has zero or more child nodes—those are nodes whose output is fed as input to the parent node.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] For example, a join node will have two child nodes, which represent the two join operands, whereas a sort node would have a single child node (the input to be sorted).
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The leaves of the tree are nodes which produce results by scanning the disk, for example by performing an index scan or a sequential scan.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The performance of a query plan is determined largely by the order in which the tables are joined.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] For example, when joining 3 tables A, B, C of size 10 rows, 10,000 rows, and 1,000,000 rows, respectively, a query plan that joins B and C first can take several orders-of-magnitude more time to execute than one that joins A and C first.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Most query optimizers determine join order via a dynamic programming algorithm pioneered by IBM's System R database project .
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The optimizer then considers combining each pair of relations for which a join condition exists.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] For each pair, the optimizer will consider the available join algorithms implemented by the DBMS.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] It will preserve the cheapest way to join each pair of relations, in addition to the cheapest way to join each pair of relations that produces its output according to a particular sort order.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Then all three-relation query plans are computed, by joining each two-relation plan produced by the previous phase with the remaining relations in the query.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Sort order can avoid a redundant sort operation later on in processing the query.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Second, a particular sort order can speed up a subsequent join because it clusters the data in a particular way.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] A SQL query to a modern relational DBMS does more than just selections and joins.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] In particular, SQL queries often nest several layers of SPJ blocks (Select-Project-Join), by means of group by, exists, and not exists operators.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] In some cases such nested SQL queries can be flattened into a select-project-join query, but not always.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Query plans for nested SQL queries can also be chosen using the same dynamic programming algorithm as used for join ordering, but this can lead to an enormous escalation in query optimization time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] So some database management systems use an alternative rule-based approach that uses a query graph model.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] One of the hardest problems in query optimization is to accurately estimate the costs of alternative query plans.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Optimizers cost query plans using a mathematical model of query execution costs that relies heavily on estimates of the cardinality, or number of tuples, flowing through each edge in a query plan.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Cardinality estimation in turn depends on estimates of the selection factor of predicates in the query.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Traditionally, database systems estimate selectivities through fairly detailed statistics on the distribution of values in each column, such as histograms.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] This technique works well for estimation of selectivities of individual predicates.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] However many queries have conjunctions of predicates such as `select count(*) from R where R.make='Honda' and R.model='Accord'`.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Query predicates are often highly correlated (for example, `model='Accord'` implies `make='Honda'`), and it is very hard to estimate the selectivity of the conjunct in general.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Poor cardinality estimates and uncaught correlation are one of the main reasons why query optimizers pick poor query plans.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] This is one reason why a database administrator should regularly update the database statistics, especially after major data loads/unloads.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Classical query optimization assumes that query plans are compared according to one single cost metric, usually execution time, and that the cost of each query plan can be calculated without uncertainty.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Both assumptions are sometimes violated in practice and multiple extensions of classical query optimization have been studied in the research literature that overcome those limitations.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Those extended problem variants differ in how they model the cost of single query plans and in terms of their optimization goal.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Classical query optimization associates each query plan with one scalar cost value.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization assumes that query plan cost depends on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Such parameters can for instance represent the selectivity of query predicates that are not fully specified at optimization time but will be provided at execution time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization therefore associates each query plan with a cost function that maps from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a one-dimensional cost space.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is usually to generate all query plans that could be optimal for any of the possible parameter value combinations.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] This yields a set of relevant query plans.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] At run time, the best plan is selected out of that set once the true parameter values become known.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The advantage of parametric query optimization is that optimization (which is in general a very expensive operation) is avoided at run time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] There are often other cost metrics in addition to execution time that are relevant to compare query plans.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] In a cloud computing scenario for instance, one should compare query plans not only in terms of how much time they take to execute but also in terms of how much money their execution costs.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Or in the context of approximate query optimization, it is possible to execute query plans on randomly selected samples of the input data in order to obtain approximate results with reduced execution overhead.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] In such cases, alternative query plans must be compared in terms of their execution time but also in terms of the precision or reliability of the data they generate.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Multi-objective query optimization models the cost of a query plan as a cost vector where each vector component represents cost according to a different cost metric.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Classical query optimization can be considered as a special case of multi-objective query optimization where the dimension of the cost space (i.e., the number of cost vector components) is one.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Different cost metrics might conflict with each other (e.g., there might be one plan with minimal execution time and a different plan with minimal monetary execution fees in a cloud computing scenario).
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Therefore, the goal of optimization cannot be to find a query plan that minimizes all cost metrics but must be to find a query plan that realizes the best compromise between different cost metrics.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] What the best compromise is depends on user preferences (e.g., some users might prefer a cheaper plan while others prefer a faster plan in a cloud scenario).
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Multi-objective parametric query optimization generalizes parametric and multi-objective query optimization.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Plans are compared according to multiple cost metrics and plan costs may depend on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The cost of a query plan is therefore modeled as a function from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a multi-dimensional cost space.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is to generate the set of query plans that can be optimal for each possible combination of parameter values and user preferences.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] A number of tools display query execution plans to show which operations have the highest processing cost.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Microsoft SMS, ApexSQLPlan, Hana, and Tableau are some examples.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] Fixing these issues found in these plans can shave tens of percent execution time, and in some cases can cut two-dimensional searches to linear ones.
[src:trino-presto/query-optimization] One of the primary and simplest optimization checklists is to use operations that most RDMS are designed to execute efficiently.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] In January 2019, the original creators of Presto, Martin Traverso, Dain Sundstrom, and David Phillips, created a fork of the Presto project.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] They initially kept the name Presto and used the PrestoSQL web handle to distinguish it from the original PrestoDB project.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Simultaneously, they announced the Presto Software Foundation.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] The foundation is a not-for-profit organization dedicated to the advancement of the Presto open source distributed SQL query engine.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] In December 2020, PrestoSQL was rebranded as Trino.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] The Trino Software Foundation, code base, and all other PrestoSQL assets were renamed as part of the rebrand.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Presto and Trino were originally designed and developed by Martin, Dain, David, and Eric Hwang at Facebook to allow data analysts to run interactive queries on its large data warehouse in Apache Hadoop.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino shares the first six years of development with the Presto project.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] To learn more about the earlier history of Trino, you can reference the Presto history section.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino is used in many data platforms and products from cloud providers and other vendors.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Customization of these products varies from pure Trino usage to heavily customized systems to run a data platform or integration in specialized data platforms for usage with specific data.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Examples include Amazon Athena, Starburst Galaxy, Dune, and many others.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] It runs on a cluster of servers that contains two types of nodes, a **coordinator** and a **worker**.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino adheres to the ANSI SQL standard and includes various parts of the following ANSI specifications: SQL-92, SQL:1999, SQL:2003, SQL:2008, SQL:2011, SQL:2016, SQL:2023.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino supports the separation of compute and storage and may be deployed both on-premises and in the cloud.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino has a Distributed computing MPP architecture.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Trino first distributes work over multiple workers by running ad-hoc partitioning operations or relying on existing partitions in the data of the underlying data store.
[src:trino-presto/trino-sql-query-engine] Once this data has reached the worker, the data is processed over pipelined operators carried out on multiple threads.
